This is an action packed week! With a .25% rate increase expected to happen on Wednesday. 

After the Fed hikes 25bp on Wednesday, will they have reached their limit, or will there be more hikes to come? Their next meeting will be in March and for now, the futures are estimating one more 25bp hike, but of course, will depend on the data. Other central banks are set to hike this week, with the European Central Bank and Bank of England expected to hike 50bp each, but it’s less likely they have reached their limit as they are behind the US and started tightening well after we began.

While the 25bp hike on Wednesday is almost a sure thing, Powell’s comments will be key for the markets. It’s likely he will continue to talk tough, especially with the jobs markets seemingly still strong.

What are your thoughts?

An ND (Neutral Density) filter is a camera lens accessory that reduces the amount of light entering the lens, allowing the creator to use longer exposures or wider apertures without overexposing the image. ND filters are neutral, meaning they don’t affect the color balance of the image, and come in different strengths, usually expressed as stops of light reduction, (the one in the video only 3 stops) allowing the creator to choose the appropriate level of reduction for their shooting situation.

Even the Federal Reserve Bank Knows How To Get You To Open An Email

The annual inflation rate in the US slowed only slightly to 6.4% in January of 2023 from 6.5% in December, less than market forecasts of 6.2%. Still, it is the lowest reading since October of 2021. A slowdown was seen in food prices (10.1% vs 10.4%) while cost of used cars and trucks continued to decline (-11.6% vs -8.8%). In contrast, the cost of shelter increased faster (7.9% vs 7.5%) as well as energy (8.7% vs 7.3%), with gasoline prices rising 1.5%, reversing from a 1.5% decline in December. On the other hand, both fuel oil (27.7% vs 41.5%) and electricity prices slowed (11.9% vs 14.3%). Although inflation has shown signs of peaking at 9.1% in June last year, it remains more than three times above the Fed’s 2% target and continues to point to a broad-based advance on the general price level, particularly services and housing. Compared to December, the CPI rose 0.5%, the most in three months, mostly due to the higher cost of shelter, food, gasoline, and natural gas.

Let’s clear the confusion around the asset test requirement for hometown heroes down payment assistance!

Have you been told that you need to pass an asset test to qualify for down payment or closing cost assistance? Well, let me tell you, that’s not entirely true.

So, as of today, May 11th, there’s no asset test requirement for the “hometown heroes” program. So, go ahead and take advantage of this program if you’re eligible.

🏠 Have you been hearing about a 1% down conventional loan program? The Florida Hometown Heroes program may be an even better option. Why?

🍎 Let’s compare apples to apples: the 1% down program provides a 2% grant, while Hometown Heroes offers 5% or a minimum of $10,000 up to $35,000 for your dream home. 📊 Using a $250,000 purchase price, that means you’d get $11,875 with Hometown Heroes vs $5,000 grant!

🥇 While the rocket program has some advantages (no mortgage insurance & temporary buy downs), as a Florida resident, it’s worth exploring both options to find which suits YOU best, to make sure you don’t miss out on lower monthly payments, rates, and overall cash to close savings. 👌

They will occupy one of the units and then they will be able to receive rental income on the other units to assist with her debt to income.

The real benefit to the conventional loan versus the FHA loan is that the buyer will not have to pay the upfront mortgage insurance premium that FHA Requires on all Loans. This will save a buyer 1.75% of the loan amount. 

It is my opinion that this is going to cause multi family properties to appreciate drastically over the next 12 months. If you were looking to purchase one and start building your real estate portfolio, I would highly recommend getting off the sideline now.

🎥 Yes, another multifamily property video, but this one is different. There have been some changes in how rental income is calculated for multifamily properties. 
 
📬 In a recent videos I’ve seen from others, it’s been mentioned that rental income from multifamily properties would not count if you’re purchasing the property. This isn’t entirely accurate.

🛑 The only situation where this applies is if you don’t currently own your home or have a housing expense (i.e. Pay Rent). 

⚖️ As for how rental income is calculated? Well, there’s been a shift there too. If you have a housing expense, any additional rental income from the property can offset the PITIA – that’s your principal, interest, taxes, and insurance. 

🔄 Previously, you could use this as gross effective income. For example, if you had $4,000 in expenses and $5,000 in rental income, you could use all $5,000. Using the same example, now, you can only use $4,000 to offset your mortgage expenses and the additional $1,000 is not counted. 

🚩 There are other significant rental changes, but let’s pause here for now. Digest this, and stay tuned for more updates!

#condos #fanniemae

🔎 Recently, major publications like the @miamiherald and @sunsentinel have been buzzing about a so-called “blacklist” of condos by Fannie Mae. But let’s clear the air - this list doesn’t label condos as just unapproved. It’s simply a resource for those in the residential service field, like loan officers, lenders, and brokers. 🚫

🏢 What we should be focusing on is local information. Miami-Dade, for example, has implemented an association registry, where condo associations annually post their budgets, insurance policies, and more. This gives a transparent view of a condo’s financial health. 💡

👉 However, accessing this information can be costly and confusing for the average person. The bigger issue is not the so-called “blacklist”, but the secrecy of these associations and the high costs of gaining vital information. 🕵️‍♀️

⚖️ Change is needed - for better protection of condo buyers in the Florida sales contract, and for ease of access to essential information. Let’s rally for these changes together. 👊

✍️ If you’re a writer in the South Florida market, let’s sit down and talk about these issues. We can make a change, if we focus on the right things. Let’s talk. 🤝
